  "prompt": "Why all planets are circling the sun in the same direction?",
  "response": "All planets in our solar system orbit the Sun in the same direction because they formed from the same rotating disk of gas and dust, known as the protoplanetary disk, approximately 4.6 billion years ago. Here\u2019s why:\n\n1. **Origin of the Solar System**: The solar system formed from a giant molecular cloud of gas and dust. As the cloud collapsed under its own gravity, it began to spin faster due to the conservation of angular momentum. This spinning caused the material to flatten into a disk shape, with the Sun forming at the center.\n\n2. **Conservation of Angular Momentum**: The original rotation of the cloud was preserved as it contracted. This means that the material in the disk inherited the same overall rotational direction. As the planets formed from this disk, they continued to orbit the Sun in the same direction.\n\n3. **Formation of Planets**: Planets coalesced from the material in the rotating disk. Because the disk was spinning in a consistent direction, the planets inherited this motion and began to orbit the Sun in the same direction\u2014counterclockwise when viewed from above the Sun's north pole.\n\n### Exceptions and Minor Variations:\n- **Retrograde Moons**: Some moons in the solar system orbit their planets in the opposite direction (retrograde motion). These are thought to have been captured later rather than forming in the same disk.\n- **Inclined Orbits**: A few planets, like Uranus, have highly tilted axes of rotation, but they still orbit the Sun in the same counterclockwise direction.\n\nIn summary, the shared direction of planetary orbits is a result of the conservation of angular momentum from the original rotating disk that gave birth to the solar system.",
